05046nam a22007575i 9780812291018DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979904973  a97808122910187 a10.9783/97808122910182doi  a(DE-B1597)451280  a(OCoLC)903760561  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a320.540917/672231 aMabry, Tristan James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNationalism, Language, and Muslim Exceptionalism /cTristan James Mabry. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b6 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHaney Foundation Series00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Muslim Nations -- tChapter 3. National Tongues -- tChapter 4. Modern Standard Arabs -- tChapter 5. Tongue Ties: The Kurds of Iraq -- tChapter 6. Natives of the “New Frontier”: The Uyghurs of Xinjiang -- tChapter 7. Print Culture and Protest: The Sindhis of Pakistan -- tChapter 8. Speaking to the Nation: The Kashmiris of India -- tChapter 9. From Nationalism to Islamism? The Acehnese of Indonesia -- tChapter 10. Religious Community Versus Ethnic Diversity: The Moros of the Philippines -- tChapter 11. Nationalism, Language, and Islam -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn an era of ethnopolitical conflict and constitutional change worldwide, nationalist and Islamist movements are two of the most powerful forces in global politics. However, the respective roles played by nationalism and Islamism in Muslim separatist movements have until recently been poorly understood. The conventional view foregrounds Muslim exceptionalism, which suggests that allegiance to the nation of Islam trumps ethnic or national identity. But, as Tristan James Mabry shows, language can be a far more reliable indicator of a Muslim community's commitment to nationalist or Islamist struggles.Drawing on fieldwork in Iraq, Pakistan, India, Indonesia, and the Philippines, Nationalism, Language, and Muslim Exceptionalism examines and compares the ethnopolitical identity of six Muslim separatist movements. There are variations in secularism and ethnonationalism among the cases, but the key factor is the presence or absence of a vernacular print culture—a social cement that binds a literate population together as a national group. Mabry shows that a strong print culture correlates with a strong ethnonational identity, and a strong ethnonational identity correlates with a conspicuous absence of Islamism. Thus, Islamism functions less as an incitement, more as an opportunistic pull with greater influence when citizens do not have a strong ethnonational bond. An innovative perspective firmly grounded in empirical research, Nationalism, Language, and Muslim Exceptionalism has important implications for scholars and policymakers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aPublic Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2015z9783110438741oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229101840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812291018423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812291018.jpg  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-201